ORION'S SHADOW WAR
The Three-Way Game — Master Architecture Document

I. THE THREE PLAYERS
Valerius Caelus (The Pale Court)
Goal: Control. He wants to use the chaos of the Civil War and the Dragon Crisis to establish a vampire aristocracy, with himself at its head. The Dark Brotherhood is a useful tool — a scalpel to eliminate political rivals and enforce his will from the shadows. His endgame is a Skyrim where mortals are "preserved" as willing cattle in a perfectly ordered society. He does not want chaos. He wants a stable, controllable system to take over.
The Dark Brotherhood
Goal: Resurgence. They are a fallen power, a shadow of their former glory. Their ultimate contract — the assassination of the Emperor — is not just a job; it is a statement. The act that will announce their return to the world stage and plunge the Empire into a chaos from which they can profit and rebuild.
Orion (The Fulcrum)
Goal: Usurpation. Orion's trajectory is the transition from double-agent to usurper. He is currently playing a dangerous game of appeasement between the Dark Brotherhood (Varon/Vasha) and the Pale Court (Valerius). His endgame is not to escape these factions, but to use them against each other, break the physical leash of Valerius's ring using Tonal Architecture, and seize the mantle of Vampire Lord of Skyrim for himself.
Current Status: Vampire. Valerius's Thrall (Tier 1). Dark Brotherhood Initiate (Tier 1). Carries the Ring of the Pale Regent (irremovable scrying device and tether to Valerius). Possesses the Diagnostic Song (learned from observing Hjolmar). Teaching Nora tonal engineering basics.

II. THE CORE TENSION
The beauty of this setup is that Valerius's goals and the Brotherhood's goals are, for a time, mutually beneficial but ultimately incompatible. Orion's secret third agenda — using both to destroy each other and claim the throne — adds a layer that neither faction anticipates.
Short-Term Synergy (Current Arc)
Valerius wants to weaken the Empire to make his takeover easier. The Brotherhood's contracts often align with this — targeting officials, disrupting power structures, sowing chaos. Valerius provides resources the Brotherhood needs: magical support, intel, and supernatural problem-solving. Orion can, for now, successfully serve both masters. A contract from the Brotherhood to kill a political target also serves Valerius's destabilisation goals.
Long-Term Conflict (Future Arcs)
The Breaking Point: The assassination of the Emperor. This is the Brotherhood's ultimate goal. However, continent-wide chaos is bad for Valerius's business. He doesn't want anarchy; he wants a stable system to inherit. An Empire in full-blown civil war is unpredictable and uncontrollable.
Valerius's True Goal: He doesn't want the Brotherhood to be a resurgent power. He wants them to be his power. His endgame is to have Orion either assassinate the Brotherhood's leadership and take control (as a puppet leader) or systematically turn the entire sanctuary into his personal vampire coven.
Orion's True Goal: He doesn't want to serve either master. He wants the ring off his finger, Valerius dead or neutralised, the Brotherhood indebted to or controlled by him, and the Vampire Lord title for himself. Every mission he completes for either faction is simultaneously an investment in his own coup.

III. THE MECHANICAL FRAMEWORK
The Mission Structure
Each mission follows a three-beat structure during Order of Business phases:
The Contract: Orion receives a contract from the Brotherhood.
The Whisper: Shortly after, he receives objectives from Valerius related to that contract.
The Dilemma: These objectives conflict. Orion must choose — or find a third path.
Resolution is handled through skill checks (Guile for deception, Agility for stealth, Might for combat). Outcomes shift faction standing.
Mission Types
Contracts will fall into escalating categories as the arc progresses:
Type 1 — The Aligned Hit: Both factions want the same target dead, but for different reasons and with different methods. The dilemma is execution, not objective. Brotherhood wants it loud and terrifying. Valerius wants it surgical and deniable. Orion's choice of method signals which master he's prioritising.
Type 2 — The Divergent Contract: The Brotherhood wants a target dead. Valerius wants them alive — turned, enthralled, or leveraged. Orion must kill or preserve, and convince the losing faction that their objective was met. Requires deception, staging, and misdirection.
Type 3 — The Impossible Contract: Both factions want mutually exclusive outcomes that cannot be faked. Orion must openly choose a side or attempt an improvised third path that risks exposure to both. These are the breaking points.
Type 4 — The Endgame Contract: One faction orders Orion to move against the other directly. Kill the Brotherhood's leadership for Valerius, or assassinate the Emperor against Valerius's wishes. No middle ground. No deception. Choose.

