V. ACTIVE CONTRACTS
The Grelod Contract (Riften — IMMEDIATE)
Status: Contract received via courier. Party has just arrived at Riften's gates.
Brotherhood Objective: Assassinate Grelod the Kind at Honorhall Orphanage. The client (Aventus Aretino) requires that she suffer and that the children know they are free. Varon is present to ensure a flawless, untraceable execution.
Pale Court Objective: Valerius recognises Honorhall Orphanage as a prime intelligence network — children move unseen, hear everything, are ignored by adults. He commands Orion to kill Grelod but frame a rival faction (e.g., the Thieves Guild). Crucially, he commands Orion to Enthrall the assistant, Constance Michel, using the Ring, turning the orphanage into a Pale Court asset.
The Danger: Maven Black-Briar protects Grelod (who supplies the Thieves Guild with child recruits). If Orion is caught, or if the hit traces back to the Wardens, Maven will destroy the party politically and physically. The party is currently being celebrated as heroes of Riften thanks to Danica's plague work — any connection to a murder in an orphanage would be catastrophic.
The Dilemma: A clean Brotherhood kill is straightforward but wastes the intelligence opportunity. Valerius's plan is more valuable but exponentially more dangerous and requires using Enthrallment (a new ability Orion hasn't tested). And Maven is watching everything in her city.
Complication — Varon and Saijah: Varon has begun overriding Orion's priorities for Saijah's sake. If Saijah wants to go to the Eldergleam instead of Windhelm for the Hroki contract, Varon will support her over the Brotherhood timeline. This is unprecedented — Varon's professional loyalty cracking for personal desire. Orion can exploit this or be destroyed by it.
Failure Condition: If Orion cannot complete the Grelod assassination, the Dark Brotherhood will turn on him. Varon will be reassigned from handler to executioner. Orion's only leverage against this outcome is Saijah — Varon's feelings for her are the one crack in his professional armour.
The Hroki Contract (Windhelm — MID-TERM)
Status: Outstanding. Hroki is now a celebrated Captain of the Guard in a highly fortified city.
Brotherhood Objective: Assassinate Hroki. Difficulty has exponentially increased since the contract was issued — Hroki is no longer a minor NPC but a public figure with military protection.
Pale Court Objective: Do not kill Hroki. Valerius requires him alive as leverage against Galmar Stone-Fist.
The Danger: This is the breaking point. Orion cannot satisfy both factions. He must find a way to fake Hroki's death (fooling Varon) or openly declare his loyalty to Valerius (making an enemy of the Brotherhood). There is no Type 2 middle ground here — this is a Type 3 contract.

VI. MECHANICAL PROGRESSION
Current Abilities
Tonal Magic: Diagnostic Song (Learned from observing Hjolmar)
Action: Major Action
Execution: Orion plays a sustained, focused note aimed at a single target. Requires a Magic or Tonal Engineering roll.
Effect (Success): Learns the target's current HP and FP totals, AND one unique ability or passive trait (GM's discretion based on tactical relevance).
Effect (Exceptional Success): Also detects hidden conditions — poison, enchantment, possession, illusions, disguised entities.
Drawback: Strictly audible. Cannot be used in stealth without revealing position.
Upcoming Abilities
Pale Court Magic: Enthrallment (Taught via the Ring — triggers during Grelod contract)
Action: Major Action
Execution: Orion must lock eyes with a terrified, subjugated, or willing mortal and channel the Ring of the Pale Regent's magic. Requires a Hard (-2) Magic vs. Guile check against the target.
Effect (Success): Target is Enthralled. They retain personality and memories, but ultimate loyalty is magically bound to the Pale Court. They obey Orion's commands, provided they do not conflict with Valerius's overarching will.
Significance: Teaches Orion how vampiric domination works without biting or blood-sharing. Pure psychological control. Also demonstrates the Ring's capabilities in a way that makes Orion understand both its power and its danger — the same thing Valerius is doing to him.
The Endgame Ability: The Song of Severance
The Problem: The Ring of the Pale Regent cannot be removed. It acts as a scrying device and a physical tether to Valerius. Valerius sees what Orion sees. Hears what Orion hears. The ring is a leash.
The Solution: Orion learned from the Arcanaeum that Daedric bindings of this nature can only be broken by the true death of the creator (Valerius) OR by advanced Tonal Architecture. Orion must develop a specific "Song of Severance" — a frequency that shatters the ring's enchantment without destroying his own hand.
Requirements: Further study with Nora (who is learning tonal engineering from him, creating a feedback loop of shared knowledge) or interaction with remaining Dwemer/Atmoran tonal technology. GEAR is a potential resource — the automaton was built by Dwemer tonal engineers and could provide critical data on breaking enchantments through sound, though GEAR has no concept of why Orion would want to do this and would answer questions with complete, indiscriminate honesty.
The Risk: Attempting the Song of Severance and failing doesn't just leave the ring intact — it alerts Valerius that Orion is trying to break free. One shot. It has to work.

VII. THE ENDGAME — THREE PATHS
Path A: The Vampire Prince (Side with Valerius)
Orion accepts the Vampire Lord transformation when offered. He sabotages the Emperor's assassination, shatters the Brotherhood, and becomes Valerius's right hand. The Brotherhood hunts him as their ultimate betrayer. He rules as a prince in Valerius's court — powerful, protected, and forever a subordinate to the being who made him.
The Trap: This is what Valerius wants. The Vampire Lord transformation binds Orion to his bloodline more deeply than the ring ever could. He trades one leash for a stronger one. He gains power but loses autonomy permanently.
Path B: The Dark Brother (Side with the Brotherhood)
Orion refuses the Vampire Lord transformation and carries out the Emperor's assassination. He becomes a legend within the guild — a Silencer who brought down an Empire. But Valerius, betrayed and furious, will hunt him for the rest of his un-life. The ring remains. The leash remains. He is free of one master and at war with another.
The Trap: The Brotherhood's resurgence makes Orion a high-value target for every intelligence service on the continent. He traded a secret war for a public one.
Path C: The Usurper (The True Endgame)
Orion plays both factions to the breaking point. He develops the Song of Severance. He feeds Valerius enough success to reach Protégé status — close enough to strike. He feeds the Brotherhood enough kills to reach Silencer — trusted enough to access their leadership. Then he breaks the ring, eliminates Valerius (or forces him into a position of weakness), and seizes control of whichever faction is left standing. He becomes the Vampire Lord of Skyrim on his own terms — not as Valerius's heir, but as the man who destroyed his maker and built something new from the wreckage.
The Trap: This path requires perfection. One misstep — one failed deception, one cracked cover, one moment where either faction realises they're being played — and both turn on him simultaneously. A vampire lord and an assassin's guild hunting the same target is not survivable.
The Variable — Saijah: Varon's feelings for Saijah are the one element neither Valerius nor the Brotherhood anticipated. If Orion can manipulate Varon through Saijah — or if Saijah genuinely changes Varon's loyalties — the Brotherhood's enforcement mechanism (Varon as executioner) collapses. This is Orion's single greatest asset and his most dangerous gamble. If Saijah discovers she's being used as leverage, she will never forgive him.

